  "description": "2026-03-02 update: simulated internet blackout losses put United States first, China second, with world exposure at $30.97B/day.",
  "excerpt": "2026-03-02 / day 3: a same-length local internet blackout simulation for the world and top economies, with United States and China leading the modeled daily losses and the world scenario at $30.97B/day.",
  "body_paragraphs": [
    "This post does not say these economies are currently losing money because Iran is offline. It uses Iran's blackout duration as a time clock and simulates what a same-length domestic internet blackout would cost each economy on day 3.",
    "Under the world scenario, a blackout of this length implies $30.97B in daily GDP loss and $85.28B in cumulative loss since day 1.",
    "For the large-economy scenarios, the biggest simulated daily losses today are: United States: $9.05B/day; China: $4.86B/day; Germany: $1.32B/day.",
    "Method: 2025 nominal GDP baseline × country-specific digital sensitivity coefficient × an outage-duration escalation curve that gets harsher as the blackout continues."
  ],
